  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "likewise",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] We might have expected ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "therefore",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as P.B.V. following Vulg. loosely renders: but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "likewise",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is significant. There is a correspondence and equivalence between the sin and its punishment Cp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Micah 2:1-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the idea is worked out that the heartless oppressors who have driven the poor from their homes will be driven from the land into exile.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The doom of the wicked man is forcibly described by various figures. He fancies himself securely intrenched in the fortress of his wealth, but God will ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "break him down",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 8:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for ever",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", so that there will be no restoration of the ruins. He is at ease in his home, but God will take him as a man takes a coal from the hearth with tongs or shovel, and plucking him out of his dwelling, drive him forth as a homeless wanderer (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 28:63",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 2:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 18:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", R.V.). He is “spreading himself like a green tree in its native soil” (",
        "children": []
      },
